    {
      "note_no": "124",
      "note": "Lit., \"except such among them as are bent upon wrongdoing\" (regarding the intent implied in the use of the past tense in expressions like alladhrna zalama or alladhrna kafaru, see note 6 on verse 6 of this surah). The Qur'an stresses repeatedly that the Muslims are true followers of Abraham. This claim, however, might have been open to objection so long as they prayed in a direction other than Abraham's qiblah, the Ka'bah. The establishment of the latter as the qiblah of the followers of the Qur'an would invalidate any such argument and would leave it only to \"those who are bent upon wrongdoing\" (in this case, distorting the truth) to challenge the message of the Qur'an on these grounds."
    }
  ],
  "en_snotes_yusuf": null,
  "en_snotes_asad": "Lit., \"except such among them as are bent upon wrongdoing\" (regarding the intent implied in the use of the past tense in expressions like alladhrna zalama or alladhrna kafaru, see note 6 on verse 6 of this surah). The Qur'an stresses repeatedly that the Muslims are true followers of Abraham. This claim, however, might have been open to objection so long as they prayed in a direction other than Abraham's qiblah, the Ka'bah. The establishment of the latter as the qiblah of the followers of the Qur'an would invalidate any such argument and would leave it only to \"those who are bent upon wrongdoing\" (in this case, distorting the truth) to challenge the message of the Qur'an on these grounds.",
